Report on the results of the parallel audit of the management of the sales tax of the Czech Republic and Germany
Foreword
The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, emphasizes that the courts of auditors have the power to audit the entire public finances.
The statement calls for the courts of auditors to have the power to scrutinise tax collection as much as possible.
The Organisation of the European Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) considers taxes to be an important part of public revenue.
The thematic focus of the VI EUROSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, was the audit of public revenue by the audit courts.
One of the most important steps on the way to optimising the audit work of a Court of Auditors is to develop a special strategy for the audit of public revenue.
This is particularly true for taxes, which are the largest source of public income with a high risk of default.
As national economies are increasingly interconnected and interdependent, a situation can arise in which national audit bodies can only carry out their audit work in cooperation with the audit bodies of other states.
As an example, the examination of internationally organized fraud can be considered, which can lead to significant loss of revenue in many states.
Cooperation between the authorities is required in the fight against such crimes.
Audit bodies in this area must be prepared to work closely with each other.
The idea for an audit of the turnover tax as well as the MIAS system arose at the VI EUROSAI Congress in Bonn, which was carried out in cooperation between the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Court of Auditors.
In the course of a thorough preparation, the participating audit courts first had to familiarize themselves with the legal framework and procedures of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and in Germany.
On the basis of the analysis of the available information, we made the selection of the subjects for the examination planning.
Achieving the efficient and effective management of VAT is a long-standing problem, and individual states (in particular the EC Member States) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify the collection of VAT and create greater transparency in this area.
We are convinced that the results of our audit can not only contribute to the improvement of the work of the financial administration, but also form the basis for a proposal for an improved system of international exchange of information.
Report on the results of the parallel audit of the management of the sales tax of the Czech Republic and Germany
Introduction
Reference: CZ) 06 / 27 (DE) VIII 2 - 2005 - 1215
Subject of examination:
(CZ) Management of VAT following the accession of the Czech Republic to the European Union
(De) Examination of administrative co-operation in the field of value added tax in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 and 1925 / 2004
The Commission's audit objective is:
(CZ) The aim of the audit in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedures applied by the financial administration in the area of turnover tax following the integration of the Czech Republic into the common internal market of the European Community (hereinafter "EC") with free movement of goods and services, as well as the use of MIAS1, in particular the control of the use of the VAT exemption for intra-Community deliveries.
(De) The aim of the audit was to examine the system of intra-Community VAT control, with a focus on mutual assistance in the area of VAT, in accordance with the above-mentioned regulations.
As a result of the audit, weaknesses should be identified and recommendations should be made to remedy them.
VAT information exchange system The audits were carried out jointly by the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic ("NK") and the Bundesrech-nungshof ("BRH") of the Federal Republic of Germany, on the basis of an agreement concluded on 8 June 2006.
The focus of the cooperation was the review of selected business transactions between entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany, the exploitation of information obtained through international mutual assistance between the financial authorities, and the comparison of VAT management systems in the two states.
A joint final report on the results of the examinations was prepared in accordance with European Guideline 31 for the implementation of the INTOSAI audit standards.
The period under review covered the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005.
Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel audit
The parallel audit of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two audit bodies.
In addition to the focus on "exchange of information" under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 and Commission Regulation 1925 / 2004, other closely related aspects have also been examined, such as the registration of tax evaders, tax returns and summary notifications.
In addition, the audit also covered the legal situation with regard to cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach and the comparison of statistical data.
When comparing the systems of VAT administrations in the two states, differences were found in the following areas:
1) Registration for the purpose of VAT.
While in Germany, entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, among others, the essential criterion for registration is to exceed the turnover threshold set out in the VAT Act.
In the Czech Republic, tax evaders only receive a single tax identification number, which they also use for intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, for the purposes of turnover tax, the person entitled to tax will receive a tax number that applies only to domestic sales.
If the German tax authorities want to make intra-Community transactions, they must apply for a special identification number, the so-called UST-IdNr., to be issued.
As problems arise as a result of the different registration procedures, the rules should be harmonised within the EC (see 4.1).
2) Cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach.
In the Czech Republic, the cross-border carriage of passengers by bus and coach is tax-free, but there is a right to deduct the advance tax.
In Germany, as far as the route passes through Germany, the transport service is subject to VAT.
Efforts should be made at EC level to standardize the situation in accordance with Article 393 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006 on the common system of turnover tax (see 4.2).
3) Tax returns.
Whereas in the Czech Republic, tax receipts have to be filed only for lower-year tax periods (month or quarter), tax evaders in Germany (monthly or quarterly)
Pre-registration of sales tax and, after the end of the calendar year, an annual declaration of sales tax.
In contrast to the Czech Republic, tax authorities in Germany have to submit advance VAT declarations electronically.
The introduction of the directive on the electronic filing of VAT returns in the Czech Republic would improve the efficiency of the Czech financial administration (see 4.3).
4) Summary messages.
While tax authorities in the Czech Republic are required to submit their summaries to the Financial Services (FÄ), German tax authorities are required to submit the summaries to the CLO2.
Accordingly, the FÄ in the Czech Republic will have access to the information from the summaries immediately after they have been submitted.
The information from the summary reports will only be available to German FÄ after they have been processed by the CLO.
In order to combat VAT fraud, up-to-date information on intra-Community sales is needed as soon as possible.
The monthly submission of summaries would shorten the period between the date of turnover and the update of the MIAS data.
This would allow for a timely review of taxation in the purchaser's Member State (see 4.4), but only if all EC Member States introduce the same deadlines.
5) International exchange of information in the area of VAT.
In the event of requests for information, the Czech CLO will monitor compliance with the three-month deadline.
The German CLO does not monitor processing times.
As a result, the German financial administration has completed a significantly lower percentage of requests for information within the specified time limit.
Due to these problems, the BRH has recommended to the German CLO that the deadlines be monitored on a permanent basis (see 4.6).
6) Risk management.
Each of the two Member States is in the process of developing its own risk management system (RMS), with corresponding strengths and weaknesses.
The NAC and the BRH point out that an effective RMS cannot be developed by a Member State alone.
Successful criteria, elements or approaches of an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in all EU Member States. Otherwise, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5.).
As part of the co-operation, the two audit bodies examined selected cases of intra-Community transactions carried out between Czech and German tax entities.
Of these, 31 cases were jointly reviewed through the use of CLO's legal capabilities, where there were doubts about the correct taxation or suspicion of VAT fraud.
The Court of Auditors found that:
In some cases, the FÄ used the information obtained in the international exchange of information and re-established the tax liability of the tax authorities concerned.
In these cases, the tax authorities either unlawfully claimed the VAT exemption or did not disclose the purchase of goods in their VAT return.
In some cases, the FÄ could not use the information obtained in the exchange of information because it was incomplete or incomprehensible.
In other cases, the information could not be used because of different legal provisions in the two Member States.
In some cases, the financial administration of another Member State refused to provide the information requested.
A number of cases have been uncovered in which tax evaders have misrepresented turnover in their summaries.
As a result, the data in the MIAS were correspondingly faulty, so that the staff (the FÄ) had to find out in these cases (see 6).
Examination procedure
CR examinations
The audit was carried out between June 2006 and March 2007 by Division II - "State Budget Income" and the Territorial Audit Departments of Central Bohemia, North West Bohemia, South Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and North Moravia.
