An entrepreneur with a legal seat, registered office or establishment in the Czech Republic, whose turnover in the last 12 consecutive calendar months exceeds the amount of CZK 1,000,000, will be eligible for payment on the first day of the third month after the month in which he has exceeded the threshold (§ 94 (1) of Law No 235 / 2004 Coll., concerning turnover tax; hereinafter "Law No 235 / 2004").
The person concerned must apply for registration within 15 days of the end of the month in which he has exceeded the registration threshold.
The current legislation does not allow for the retroactive registration of a tax collector if he has exceeded the registration deadline.
An entrepreneur with a legal seat, registered office or a business establishment in the Czech Republic, who provides value added tax services or benefits exempt from VAT with the right to deduct VAT, must register for the VAT even if his turnover does not exceed CZK 1 million, but he meets other requirements mentioned in Law No 235 / 2004.
An entrepreneur with a legal seat, registered office or establishment in the Czech Republic, who does not meet any of the requirements set out in the law, can voluntarily apply for registration for VAT.
The registration procedure in accordance with Law No 337 / 1992 begins with the receipt of the registration application by the local financial officer.
If you want to register voluntarily for VAT, you have to specify in your application the date from which you apply for registration as a value-added tax holder.
The financial officer must examine the information provided by the entrepreneur, i.e. the completed application for registration with all investments.
If he has any doubts about the information contained therein, he must ask the applicant to explain, supplement or substantiate the information provided.
If, by means of a review, the financial officer has established that the entrepreneur meets the conditions for registration, he must issue a written notice on the registration and allocation of a tax number.
In the communication, the financial officer has to indicate the date of entry into force of the registration for the value added tax and the investment period for the sales tax.
The investment period is the calendar quarter, unless the entrepreneur's turnover for the previous calendar year has reached the amount of at least CZK 10,000,000.
If this is the case, the allotment period is the calendar month.
An entrepreneur, whose turnover reached at least CZK 2,000,000 in the previous calendar year, is entitled to choose the calendar month as the investment period and must inform the financial officer of this change.
The issuance of a tax number in the registration notice is always constitutive.
The tax controller must provide the tax number for any communication (including payments) with the financial officer, and in cases where a special law requires it (e.g. Law No 235 / 2004, concerning the preparation of tax documents) 3.
The tax number contains the encoding "CZ" and a basic component in the form of a general identification sign.
In the case of natural persons, this is the number of the birth certificate or another general identification mark, as far as a specific law determines it. In the case of legal persons, the general identification mark is the company identification number (in accordance with the provisions of Section 33 (12) of Law No 337 / 1992).
If the entrepreneur has failed to fulfil his obligation, despite a request from the financial officer, the local financial officer has to register him on his own initiative.
A communication will also be issued on this subject, which will be sent to the tax authorities.
In the Czech Republic, every entrepreneur authorised to do business will receive a tax number on their first registration for any type of tax.
This also applies to registration as a tax payer.
According to Law No. 235 / 2004, which entered into force on 1 January 2005, in the event of non-compliance with the tax law for the registration of turnover tax, the financial officer may require that the tax payer should have registered up to 10% of the proceeds from the tax law, which the person concerned has made unlawfully without taxation, for the period from the date on which the entrepreneur was registered as tax collector, until the date on which the tax law was passed.
The payment of the amount set in this way is considered to be a tax payment within the meaning of Section 98 (3) of Law No 235 / 2004, i.e. it is not a fine or penalty.
If the legal requirements are met, the registration of a tax payer can be deleted for two reasons:
1)
Deletion of registration at the request of the tax collector, i.e. mainly for the reason that the turnover does not reach the threshold for registration (§ 106 (1) of Law No 235 / 2004).
A tax controller can apply for the cancellation of his registration at the earliest one year after the date of entry into force mentioned in the registration notice.
2) deletion of the registration on its own initiative (§ 106 (7) of Law No. 235 / 2004), if: A) the taxable person did not perform for 12 consecutive months and did not inform the financial officer of the reasons for doing so; b) the taxable person did not fulfil his obligations under Law No. 235 / 2004; c) the former tax person no longer meets the requirements for the tax penalty.
B) Tax persons without legal seat, registered office or premises in the Czech Republic A person who is registered for tax purposes in another Member State and in the Czech Republic has neither his legal seat, place of business nor establishment, or a tax-exempt foreigner who provides services in the Czech Republic and who, in accordance with Section 108 of Law No. 235 / 2004, has to make a tax return and pay taxes on these services ("non-resident").
He must submit an application for registration with the FA Prague 1 at the latest on the day of the delivery in question.
He is obliged to indicate in this application all the UST ID numbers assigned to him in other Member States or third countries.
If a non-resident entrepreneur applies for registration later than on the day of the first tax-sensitive service provision in the Czech Republic, the FA Prague 1 has to register him retroactively, as he became subject to VAT on the day of the first tax-sensitive service provision in the Czech Republic, according to Law No 235 / 2004.
In the event of a retroactive registration, the FA Prague 1 has to demand proof (invoices or written explanations) of the performance from the companies concerned.
If a non-resident entrepreneur requests registration in the Czech Republic before performing a service for the first time, the FA Prague 1 is required to submit the performance-based contract documents.
As of December 31, 2004, 473 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered with the FA Prague 1, of which 124 were from Germany. As of December 31, 2005, a total of 951 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered, of which 233 were from Germany.
In accordance with the provisions of Section 106 (9) of Law No. 235 / 2004, the financial officer is entitled to delete the registration of a non-resident entrepreneur as of 31 January of the following calendar year if he does not accept the obligation to submit tax applications or declarations and to pay tax.
In the examination of the NK, it turned out that in the case of the submission of a tax return by post with dispatch abroad on 25 January, i.e. in accordance with the mandatory deadline for the filing of a tax return, this declaration has not yet been received by the FA until 31 January.
In cases where these facts, which are relevant to the possibility of deletion of registration, become known to the FA later than on 31 January, it is no longer possible to delete the registration of the non-resident entrepreneur for VAT in the Czech Republic in the calendar year in question.
Registration of tax evaders in Germany
According to the provisions of the tax ordinance (§ § 137, 138 AO), all business operations must be registered with the municipality and / or the competent tax office.
This registration must be made no later than one month after the start of the business.
The municipality will forward the registration to the tax authorities.
If the competent tax office determines that a business activity has been started, but has not been notified, it can also register the tax authorities on its own initiative retroactively.
In Germany, tax evaders, regardless of whether they are resident or non-resident, are penalised for registering for Zwekke's sales tax if they meet the requirements set out in Section 2 of the German VAT Act (USTG).
This does not depend on the amount of turnover achieved.
There is no voluntary registration in Germany.
There is special responsibility for entrepreneurs based abroad.
For example, the FA ChemnitzSüd is responsible for those entrepreneurs who are based in the Czech Republic.
As of April 30, 2004, INSGE- and 295 Czech entrepreneurs were registered; as of March 1, 2006, 1,050 Czech entrepreneurs were registered there.
According to the BRH's findings, these FÄ, with special responsibilities, frequently refused to register so-called bogus self-employed workers resident in the new Central and Eastern European Member States of the EC.
Since the free movement of workers is still restricted following the accession of these ten countries to the European Union, these self-employed people tried to circumvent these restrictions by setting up their own business.
These (appearances) self-employed persons do not meet the conditions laid down in Section 2 of the USTG for recognition as entrepreneurs, since they are generally dependent on a single client who determines their working time and the way in which they perform their work.
In order to be registered, the entrepreneur must fill out a questionnaire from the competent FA and provide information on the company and the business activities carried out.
The questionnaire is a pre-print that is binding on all FÄ in Germany.
It will be processed either in special organizational units within the FÄ or in the organizational units generally responsible for the tax assessment.
With the help of this requirement, a risk assessment is carried out for the individual tax person prior to the allocation of a tax number.
The structure of the tax number for domestic sales is based on certain requirements:
The first three digits are the identification number for the responsible FA, the following three (or four) digits indicate which department is responsible within the FA, the following five (or four) digits are the identification feature for the controller, the last digit is always a control digit.
If an entrepreneur wants to take part in intra-community trade, he needs a UST-IdNr in order to be able to make tax-free intra-Community deliveries.
This will be allocated by the CLO on request if the entrepreneur is registered in Germany for tax purposes.
The UST ID number will be automatically allocated by the CLO if the tax person declares intra-Community deliveries in his VAT advance filings or in his annual VAT declaration.
The UST ID number is comprised of the country code (DE) and a sequence of nine digits.
The registration of an entrepreneur can be deleted: 1. On request (for example, if he ceases to do business), but only after the completion of all tax transactions (investment of all financial years) or 2. If the financial administration determines that he no longer runs a business.
As a rule, the validity of the UST ID number depends on the validity of the VAT number.
In these cases, the FÄ must inform the CLO of the cancellation of the VAT number, so that the validity of the UST ID number can be terminated there at this time.
According to the Value Added Tax Act (§ 19 (1) USTG), domestic taxpayers do not have to pay VAT in the following cases: 1. The turnover of the previous calendar year, plus the resulting turnover tax, has not exceeded the amount of €17,500 and 2. The following year will probably not exceed the amount of €50,000.
The so-called small business owners are not entitled to charge VAT to other entrepreneurs, nor are they entitled to deduct VAT.
Although they do not have to pay a turnover tax, small business owners are obliged to register with the tax office and make an annual VAT return.
A small business owner can explain the non-application of Section 19 (1) USTG.
This declaration will be binding for the next five years.
He is then allowed to charge the sales tax and deduct the advance tax.
Non-residents can appoint a fiscal representative (Section 22a of the USTG).
The prerequisite for this is that they only make tax-free sales and waive the deduction.
The fiscal representative meets the tax obligations of the foreign entrepreneur, so that he does not have to register for the purposes of the sales tax.
The accounts state that a fiscal representative has been appointed.
Comparison and evaluation
The situation in the two states is different.
While in Germany, entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, the first requirement for registration (among others) is to exceed the threshold set out in the VAT Act.
If an entrepreneur does not exceed this threshold, he can register voluntarily.
The registration process in Germany is standardized, but differences can occur in the individual federal states due to different organisational structures.
In the Czech Republic, at the time of its first registration, the person in charge of tax will receive a tax number for any tax.
In the case of his registration for the turnover tax, this tax number also applies to intra-Community sales.
In Germany, an entrepreneur who can register for sales tax purposes receives a tax number exclusively for intra-German sales.
If the German entrepreneur wants to carry out intra-community sales, he has to apply specifically for the allocation of a UST ID number.
Both the NAC and the BRH found that the German two-step registration system in other Member States, such as the Czech Republic, which gives a single identification number for both national registration for VAT and intra-Community sales, could lead to significant misunderstandings.
On the other hand, the two-step system allows for retroactive (national registration) in cases where the tax payer does not register his business with the municipality or the relevant FA.
This retroactive registration allows for an accurate calculation of the value added tax for previous investment periods, in particular an accurate estimate of the value added tax liability.
As the different registration procedures lead to problems, the rules for the whole of the EC should be standardised.
The German parliament recently approved the introduction of a tax identification number.
This is to be allocated to every natural person after birth by the Federal Central Office for Taxation.
This number applies to natural persons resident in Germany for life.
If a natural person starts a business, the competent FA will apply for a commercial tax identification number, which serves as a UST ID number.
In the future, therefore, there should be no delay between the national registration of a tax payer and the allocation of the UST ID number.
Work on the implementation of an IT procedure for the management of the numbers has not yet been completed.
Cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach
The legal regulations in the Czech Republic
According to the provisions of Section 70 of Law No 235 / 2004, since 1 May 2004, the carriage of passengers between the individual Member States and between the Member States and third countries in the Czech Republic has been exempt from VAT and there is a right to deduction of VAT.
The exemption from VAT also applies if the carriage is carried out by persons registered in other Member States as taxable persons or by foreigners who are subject to tax in their own country.
The return journey is considered to be a separate transport operation.
If non-resident entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic do not carry out any economic activity other than the cross-border transport of passengers by bus or coach, they are not obliged to register in the Czech Republic as subject to VAT.
Cross-border passenger transport in the Czech Republic has been exempted from the VAT requirement under the Act on the accession of the Czech Republic, Annex V, Chapter 5 (1) (b).
"For the purpose of applying Article 28 (3) (b) of Directive 77 / 388 / EEC, in accordance with point 17 of Annex F to the Directive, the Czech Republic may maintain the exemption for cross-border passenger transport, either until the condition of Article 28 (4) of the Directive is fulfilled or until the same exemption is applied by any of the current Member States."
The legal regulations in Germany
In accordance with Article 46 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006, as implemented in Germany by Section 3b (1) USTG, a transport service will be carried out where the transport is carried out.
Accordingly, German taxation does not distinguish between domestic and cross-border passenger transport.
Only the domestic part of the transport service is subject to tax in Germany.
German taxation also does not differentiate between resident and non-resident (bus) entrepreneurs.
If a non-resident person is transported through Germany, the part of the carriage, which originates in Germany, is considered to be a tax-free transport.
Before providing its services in Germany, the non-resident entrepreneur must notify the competent FA of his intention to provide passenger transport services.
The latter registers it for tax purposes (compare 4.1.2) and gives a special certificate for each coach mentioned in the registration of the taxman.
The entrepreneur has to indicate his tax-sensitive transport services in a German tax return.
As of March 1, 2006, 741 Czech bus operators were registered with the FA Chemnitz-Süd.
If the transport service is provided for an entrepreneur resident in the country, the non-resident tax payer does not have to pay the turnover tax himself to the FA.
In its place, the domestic purchaser of the services must pay the turnover tax to the tax office and the net amount charged to the non-resident tax payers, which is known as the "transfer of tax liability" and is in line with Article 196 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC.
In addition to the registration by a non-resident tax collector and his income tax return, the German tax administration has several means of verifying the correctness of the tax return with regard to tax breaks:
Mobile customs control groups are examining the certificates of buses registered abroad, which are used to transport passengers through Germany.
After each inspection, the mobile control groups transmit an inspection protocol to the relevant FA.
If the bus driver does not have a valid certificate, the mobile control group can require the bus driver to pay the VAT before continuing his journey.
The non-resident taxpayer can deduct the value added tax paid in this way from the tax liability stated in his tax return.
If the FA has doubts about the accuracy of a VAT return, it can order an audit to be carried out by the FA, or it can use the means of mutual assistance referred to in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 (see point 4.6).
Even if the foreign taxpayer refuses to pay the legally established turnover tax, the FA can ask for mutual assistance in accordance with Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC.
The BRH considers these means of mutual assistance in tax matters to be too burdensome in relation to the low cost of VAT on tax-sensitive passenger transport to check the VAT return or compliance with the tax penalty by a non-resident bus operator.
In particular, checking the books of a non-resident tax collector causes disproportionately high costs for the tax collector himself and for the financial administration.
The latter must examine the foreign books, which requires not only knowledge of the foreign language, but also of the foreign accounting principles.
Accordingly, such an audit can be expected to take more time than that of a resident tax resident, although the audit is limited to the number of passenger carriages taking place in Germany.
On the other hand, the non-resident taxpayer must accept not only the audit rights of his national financial administration, but also those of the other Member States, as far as he carries out passenger transport there.
In addition, for each Member State in which a single carriage of persons is carried out, the taxable person must comply with all existing tax provisions in the various languages and on the basis of the forms provided by the financial authorities of the relevant EC Member States.
As a result, the correct taxation of cross-border passenger services leads to a disproportionately high administrative burden.
Comparison and evaluation
The legal situation is different in the two states.
In the Czech Republic, passenger transport between different EC Member States, as well as between Member States and third countries, is exempt from VAT under the Act on the accession of the Czech Republic to the EC.
In Germany, the transport service is subject to turnover tax in accordance with the transport route that originates in German territory.
If a non-resident tax controller provides such a transport service for the first time, he must notify the relevant FA beforehand.
This registers the tax payer, who has to declare the tax-deductible portion of the transport service in a tax return in Germany.
Law enforcement in Germany is very time-consuming.
At least three out of four Czech tax authorities registered with the FA Chemnitz-Süd have passenger transport as a business purpose.
The amount of tax in question is quite low in relation to the administrative burden.
Member States - which collect VAT in accordance with Article 46 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006 on the common system of value added tax - have a high administrative burden in relation to the relevant tax revenue.
In order to avoid the disproportionately high costs of investing in VAT, cross-border passenger transport should only be subject to tax in one Member State.
This could be the state where the carriage begins or where the service provider is based.
Such a form of taxation would require an amendment to Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006.
Sales tax returns
Filing and processing of VAT returns in the Czech Republic
To the extent that the law does not stipulate otherwise, even if no tax liability has been incurred, the entrepreneur will be penalised for issuing a VAT return on the pre-print provided by the Ministry of Finance within 25 days of the expiration of the tax period.
The tax liability arises at the expiration of the deadline for filing the VAT return. In accordance with law no. 235 / 2004, the VAT on the import of goods is excluded from this regulation. Here, the due date of the tax is determined by the customs regulations.
If, as a result, there is an above-average deductible advance tax claim, this amount will be refunded to the tax payer within 30 days of setting this deduction, without the need to make an application for it.
The time limit is not applied in cases where the financial officer initiates a tax procedure with regard to the tax liability of the tax payer.
In accordance with § 73 (11) of Law No. 235 / 2004, the right to deduct VAT can be asserted at the latest with the regular tax return for the last tax period of the calendar year in which the right to deduct VAT arose.
At the end of this period, the deduction can still be claimed within three years of the end of the tax period, during which the claim would have been possible for the first time.
In order to do this, however, it is necessary to submit a supplementary VAT return.
An amendment to Law No 235 / 2004, which entered into force on 1 January 2005, allows the filing of a supplementary VAT return only for the period during which the right to deduct VAT could have been invoked for the first time.
A tax collector must make a supplementary VAT return if: A) the sum of the corrections leads to an increase in the tax liability, b) he makes corrections that do not change the last known tax liability, but only change the previous information, c) he makes corrections to the turnover tax rate and the tax liability in accordance with § 49 of Law No 235 / 2004.
A tax collector can make a supplementary VAT return if the sum of the corrections reduces the tax liability.
The taxpayer must file the supplementary tax return by the end of the month, which follows the month in which the facts in question were established.
The sales tax declaration can be made electronically either via the Internet or by means of data carriers.
The delivery via the Internet can be done with a certified electronic signature or without it.
If it is carried out without an electronic signature, it must also be submitted to data carriers.
The preprint for the VAT return contains separate lines for the indication of the value of intra-Community deliveries and purchases.
The value of related services must be stated in separate lines of the VAT return.
Some headings are used for automated primary checks within the framework of the Atis system.
The value of the goods delivered to other EC Member States to persons registered there as subject to tax will be compared with the data provided by the Czech tax authorities in their summaries.
With the help of MIAS, the value of purchases of goods from other Member States from persons registered there as subject to tax will be compared with the information provided in the summaries of the tax authorities from other EC Member States.
Within the framework of the Atis system, the FA will carry out a credibility check of the VAT returns.
This is done automatically, as the VAT return cannot be processed without the prior examination.
The credibility test includes a calculation of the standards for credibility and an assessment of the risks of VAT returns.
In accordance with the provisions of Section 37 (1) of Law No 337 / 1992, the FA may repeatedly impose a fine of up to CZK 2 million on persons who do not comply with their non-monetary obligations under this or a special tax law or a decision under that law.
Automated tax information system - automated tax information system used by the Czech tax authorities to provide technical support for tax collection.
