Filing and processing of tax returns in Germany
In Germany, a distinction is made between monthly or quarterly VAT pre-registration and the annual VAT return.
Those who are penalised for submitting VAT advance applications must nevertheless make an annual VAT return.
Even small business owners who are not hired to pay the VAT will have to make an annual VAT return.
The tax payers are, in principle, suspended until the 10th day after the expiration of the calendar quarter, in which the turnover tax is generated, to submit a pre-registration for VAT (§ 18 (2) USTG).
However, if the VAT debt in the previous year is more than €6,136 or if it is a newly founded company, the entrepreneur is penalised for submitting monthly VAT advance declarations no later than the 10th day after the expiration of the month in question.
The tax collector can also choose to submit monthly VAT advance applications if he has received a refund of €6,136 in the previous year (Section 18 (2a) USTG).
If the annual turnover tax is no more than €512, neither VAT advance declarations nor VAT returns are to be made.
A resulting VAT liability is to be paid 10 days after the end of the tax period.
A refund can lead to a more thorough audit by the financial administration.
There are no (legal) deadlines for the processing of VAT returns and for the refund of VAT overpayments.
In order to receive a timely refund, a security can be offered for the refund amount.
As a matter of principle, tax returns, including refunds, must be processed quickly.
The German VAT Act allows for an extension of these (surrender and / or payment) deadlines (§ 18 (6) USTG).
The extension of the deadline must be requested separately.
If it is granted, the pre-registration of VAT and the corresponding payments may be made one month later. However, in the case of monthly reports, a special advance payment must be made for this.
This payment will be offset against the VAT liability established for the pre-filing period in December.
If an error is discovered, the entrepreneur must submit a corrected VAT advance notification.
There is no "supplementary" tax return.
Once the VAT declaration to be filed by 31 May of the following year has been submitted to the tax office, the entrepreneur will no longer be able to correct an incorrect VAT advance notification, but only the incorrect annual VAT return.
Corrections to this VAT return to the advantage or disadvantage of the person in charge of the tax are possible within four years of the end of the year in which the first VAT return was made.
At the end of this four-year period, a VAT return can usually only be corrected in cases of careless tax cuts or tax evasion.
The tax authorities are required to submit the VAT advance declarations electronically.
The FÄ can grant exceptions to this rule in order to avoid undue hardship.
The annual tax return can be made in paper form or via the Internet, with or without certification.
If the levy is made without certification, the tax payer must also make the statement on paper and with his personal signature.
If no VAT advance declarations or declarations are made, the tax administration is entitled to make a rough estimate of the turnover achieved by the tax payer.
In the event of a late charge, the tax payer can be charged with a delay surcharge (up to 10% of the tax liability or up to an amount of €25,000).
In an earlier audit, the BRH found that the FÄ often did not charge this delay surcharge.
In cases where the FÄ levied the delay surcharges, the amount was set unevenly and arbitrarily.
The delay surcharge therefore misses its purpose of reducing the average delay, particularly in the submission of the annual VAT return.
The preprint of the VAT return contains separate lines for information on the value of intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions.
There are also separate lines for the purchase of services.
Non-taxable sales are to be stated in a separate line of the VAT return.
The VAT declarations filed on paper must either be scanned or electronically recorded by specially designated staff.
The data of electronically filed tax returns are directly available to the tax authorities.
