Comparison and evaluation
In the Czech Republic, tax payers must submit their VAT returns no later than 25 days after the end of the tax period.
Depending on the turnover of the tax payer, the tax period is either the calendar quarter or the calendar month.
In Germany, depending on the amount of their tax liability in the previous year, the tax authorities must submit their advance applications no later than 10 days after the end of the calendar quarter or the calendar month.
The annual VAT declaration must be made no later than 31 May of the following year.
The decision to issue an annual tax return has a number of advantages and disadvantages:
+ After the end of the calendar year, the tax payer can correct the errors in the monthly advance filings by submitting a single VAT return;
- if the tax authority corrects its information on intra-Community transactions, the correction cannot be assigned to a specific reporting period of the ZM;
- The federal states do not match MIAS data on intra-Community purchases of German tax evaders until the annual sales tax declarations have usually been processed.
According to the registration (see 4.1.3), German entrepreneurs have to make a tax return regardless of the amount of their turnover.
This deadline will enable the German financial administration to verify compliance with the turnover ceiling for small business owners.
In addition, the competent FA can compare the annual VAT declaration with the corresponding declarations for direct taxes and with the annual accounts of the company concerned.
In the Czech Republic, the tax authorities can only check the level of turnover on the basis of the income tax declaration issued.
In contrast to the current regulations in the Czech Republic, German tax authorities are pilloried for the electronic filing of the VAT advance application.
The introduction of the tax bill for electronic tax returns in the Czech Republic would increase the efficiency of the Czech financial administration.
Summary messages
Submission and processing of summary reports in the Czech Republic
In accordance with the provisions of Section 102 of Law No 235 / 2004, an entrepreneur who delivers goods to a person registered in another Member State for tax purposes must submit such summaries ("zm" below).
The value of the goods delivered is stated in the zm always in Czech currency, broken down according to the UST-IdNr7, the individual tax authorities under which they are registered in the other Member State.
Information on services is not provided in the ZM.
Tax payers with a calendar monthly or quarterly tax period will have to hand over the zm to the local FA at the latest on the 25th day after the end of each quarter.
Incorrect data must be corrected within 15 days after the error has been detected.
Faulty data in the zm will always be replaced by the data from the correction zm.
Similar to the tax returns, the tax authorities can also surrender the ZM electronically.
If a tax collector does not give up zm or rectification zm, even though he is penalised for this under Law No 235 / 2004, the financial officer must ask him to surrender the relevant zm and, in so doing, assign the consequences of the non-levy. If non-monetary liabilities are not met, the financial officer is entitled to impose repeated fines of up to CZK 2 million in accordance with Section 37 of Law No 337 / 1992.
In its investigation, the NK found that the FÄ mostly did not use their power to impose fines on their defaulting tax evaders.
In particular, in the case of the ZM levy, the tax evaders are not sufficiently motivated to fulfil their obligations, as the failure to levy a ZM does not affect the amount of their tax liability.
According to Section 102 (5) of Law No. 235 / 2004, the financial officer is obliged to check the information in the ZM or rectification ZM, to remove all ambiguities and to use the information to determine the tax liability.
