Corrections entered by the financial officer, without a correction rate being issued by the tax controller, do not replace the tax controller's decision to issue a correction ZM, but only lead to the correction of the data in the MIAS, so that they are up-to-date, complete and accurate.
The data from the ZM will be sent to the Member States concerned.
Only the national financial authority designated for cooperation with the other Member States in the area of VAT is allowed to transmit and receive this data.
This is the CLO (in the Czech Republic, this function is carried out by the Department for International Mutual Assistance in the area of VAT in the Ministry of Finance), and the "O _ MCTL" message is automatically received by the CLO from the other Member States.
It contains all incorrect UST-IdNr., which were specified in the transmitted ZM-lines.
If the incorrect UST ID number is used in some of the transmitted lines of the ZM or the corrected ZM, an entry will be made to the list of the wrong UST ID.
The list includes a "Notification of doubts regarding UST-IdNr."
The financial officer checks the data and enters the result of the review into the system.
When purchasing goods from another Member State, the tax collector must state this in his VAT return and enter the value of the purchase in the corresponding lines of the VAT return.
Selected cases of differences between the values of the purchases made by the Czech tax authorities in their VAT return and those of the supplier from the other Member State in its zm values for the delivery of goods will be passed on by the CLO to the relevant FA for examination.
The staff there will have to investigate the deviations.
There can then be three different situations:
A) The value indicated by the Czech acquirer in the relevant sections of his VAT return is lower than the value of the deliveries indicated by suppliers from other EC Member States.
In this case, the financial officer checks the accuracy of the information.
B) The difference is zero.
This situation can be caused either by a change in the information within the EC (the foreign supplier corrects its ZM) or by a change in the information in the VAT return (the Czech tax authority, meanwhile, makes a supplementary VAT return on its own initiative).
In this case, it is at the discretion of the financial officer to check the accuracy of the information contained in the VAT return.
C) The value of goods purchased from other Member States, as indicated by the Czech tax authorities in their VAT return, is higher than the value of their supplies reported by the suppliers of the other EC Member States.
Here, in turn, it is up to the financial officer to verify the accuracy of the information.
After reviewing the differences and clarifying the reasons for their occurrence, the financial officer gives the results of his review in Atis.
These results will be sent to the CLO.
