Submission and processing of summary reports in Germany
Traders who make intra-Community deliveries from Germany to other EU Member States or take part in triangular transactions must surrender quarterly zm, in which intra-Community deliveries are listed according to purchasers (§ 18a (1) USTG).
The ZM must be delivered no later than the 10th day of the month following the calendar quarter in question.
If a long-term extension is granted for the submission of the VAT advance applications, this also applies to the ZM.
The ZM are to be handed over to the CLO.
Since January 1, 2007, the electronic levy has been punctuated.
The responsible FA can allow exemptions for individual tax breaks in order to avoid undue hardship.
If the tax payer finds that the ZM was faulty, he is paused to submit a correction within a month.
In the case of non-payment of the zm, the CLO initiates an enforcement procedure.
This includes the following steps: - first remembrance - second reminder, coupled with the threat that a penalty will be imposed and - fixing the penalty.
Although the German tax code allows for a penalty payment of up to €25,000 (§ 329 AO), the CLO sets penalties of €125, 250 and 500 in three stages.
In addition, Section 26a (1) No. 5 of the USTG determines that the tax payer acts unlawfully if he or she intentionally or lightly gives away a ZM not correctly, not completely or not in time, or if he or she does not correct a ZM or does not rectify it in time.
This infringement can be punishable by a fine of up to €5,000.
Data on intra-Community deliveries cannot be entered into the MIAS by the FÄ, because the processing of the ZM is solely the responsibility of the CLO.
The data of the zm will only be stored with the CLO.
The information from the summarising messages will only be available to the FÄ after they have been processed by the CLO.
The deadlines for processing ZM are laid down in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003.
The ZM data must be stored within three months of the calendar quarter in question (in MIAS).
In the case of incorrect UST ID number in the ZM German tax authorities, the German CLO will receive a notification "O _ MCTL" from the other Member State.
The CLO then turns to the entrepreneur and asks for the correct data.
If the CLO fails to get the correct information, the case will be handed over to the relevant FA.
It is then up to him to ask for the correct information.
In the course of its audit, the BRH found that most entrepreneurs corrected the UST ID number at the request of the CLO.
However, the memory, as well as the threat and imposition of up to three consecutive fines, takes too much time when a tax evader may be involved in cross-border carousel fraud.
The cases, which were eventually reported to the competent FÄ, were usually completed within one to two months.
The relevant FA refused to grant the tax exemption for the reported intra-Community deliveries in 73% of these cases.
If the taxman presented the correct UST ID number, the FA asked him to submit a corrected ZM to the CLO, because the FÄ cannot correct the MIAS data themselves.
The BRH found that neither the FÄ nor the CLO controlled the delivery of the corrected zm.
Therefore, the tax authorities often did not comply with the request. Since the CLO does not have access to the data of the VAT returns, no comparison is made between the information given in the VAT advance declarations or the VAT return on goods deliveries with the corresponding information in the ZM before these data are sent to the CLO of the other Member States.
This comparison can only be made by the FÄ, which is usually done in the preparation of a special VAT check.
Data received from other Member States will be processed by the CLO.
Incorrect UST ID numbers will be identified and reported to the affected Member States.
The data will be used to control employment tax in the FÄ.
As soon as they are available in the system, it compares the CLO with the data from previous calendar quarters.
If they meet certain criteria (see 5.2), control notifications will be drawn up and sent to the relevant FÄ.
This happens on an ongoing basis, whereas the acquisition data of all VAT holders is later compiled and forwarded to the FÄ.
The risk management system (RMS) for the investment process then compares this data with those for intra-community purchases.
The system checks fully (only) those entrepreneurs who are not fully entitled to deduct the advance tax.
Comparison and evaluation
In the Czech Republic, tax evaders who have made intra-Community deliveries to a person registered for VAT in another Member State will have to surrender a ZM to the local FA within 25 days of the end of the calendar quarter.
The FÄ process the ZM and transmit the data to the CLO.
In the case of FÄ, the values of intra-Community deliveries reported by the tax authorities will be compared with the values of intra-Community deliveries indicated by the same tax authorities in their VAT returns.
The results of the settlement will be taken into account in the framework of the tax setting.
In Germany, tax evaders who have made intra-Community deliveries are liable to pay quarterly interest within the first 10 days of the following calendar quarter.
Since 1 January 2007, the tax authorities have been required to submit the ZM electronically to the CLO.
The data from the ZM will only be available to the FÄ after they have been processed by the CLO.
Both in the Czech Republic and in Germany, the tax authorities only indicate the deliveries of goods in the ZM.
The provision of services is not specified in the ZM. Unlike the Czech FÄ, the German FÄ cannot itself correct incorrect information in individual lines of the ZM issued.
Due to this limited access to the German MIAS data, incorrect UST ID number was not corrected even if the tax controller reported the correct UST ID number to the FA.
The German tax administration does not compare the information on intra-Community deliveries, which German tax authorities make in their VAT advance declarations, with the information provided by the corresponding ZM.
Differences between the data from the pre-registration and the ZM are not regularly revealed before the German CLO sends the MIAS data to other Member States.
On the basis of the BRH's findings, it is clear that a comparison would improve the reliability of the MIAS data transmitted.
The data provided by other Member States on deliveries of goods to Czech tax authorities will be compared in the Czech Republic with the data on purchases of goods provided by the Czech tax authorities in their VAT returns.
The Czech CLO makes a separate comparison for each calendar quarter.
The most serious cases of deviations will be referred to the FÄ for examination.
Unlike the Czech financial administration, the German financial administration does not generally examine the taxation of intra-Community purchases.
Such general control will only be carried out in the case of tax evaders who are not fully entitled to deduction.
In addition, the German tax administration only controls the taxation of intra-Community purchases by other tax authorities if the RMS has drawn up an audit notice or if the tax authority has already been selected for an audit.
This procedure relieves FÄ of the need to clarify the reasons for the differences that arise.
On the other hand, the detection of VAT fraud depends on the quality of the RMS.
In order to combat carousel fraud, up-to-date information on intra-Community purchases must be available as early as possible.
The current ZM system, in particular MIAS, provides financial authorities with information that may well be six months old.
This time delay could be reduced to up to four months if the tax payers had to surrender monthly zm.
The monthly levy would only increase the administrative burden insignificantly, since the majority of tax evaders in the Czech Republic and Germany are already obliged to submit monthly VAT returns or pre-filings, and for which no more information is required than for the VAT returns or advance declarations.
In order to avoid red tape, the levy of the zm could be linked to the submission of VAT returns or advance declarations.
However, a break with the monthly levy of zm would create more periodic discrepancies between the information on intra-Community deliveries and those on intra-Community purchases, and would increase the flow of data between CLOs.
In 2006, the federal government considered the general introduction of monthly zm.
The implementation failed due to the concerns of the federal states.
They feared that a monthly transfer of MIAS data to the CLOs of other Member States could lead to misunderstandings and confusion.
In order for the allocation to the monthly levy to be effective, it is necessary to agree on the uniform monthly levy at European level, so that a monthly update of the MIAS data is possible.
