International exchange of information at level 3
Implementation of the international exchange of information in the Czech Republic
The international exchange of information allows financial officials to obtain information from other Member States on intra-Community transactions as well as on the tax authorities who have carried them out.
Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 on mutual assistance in the field of value added tax, repealing Directive (EEC) No 218 / 92 (hereinafter "Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003"), distinguishes between two basic types of exchange of information: Exchange of information on request and spontaneous exchange of information (without prior request).
The international exchange of information on request is carried out through a request for information (Request for Information RFI) using the standardized SCAC form.
Financial officials in the Czech Republic are sending their RFI or their responses to a received RFI through the Financial Directorate to the CLO, which is concerned about translating the information provided in the standardised SCAC preprint into the foreign language and passing it on to the other Member States.
In addition, the CLO receives requests for information (RFI) from other Member States and the responses to sent requests. It is concerned about their translation into the Czech Republic and their distribution to the relevant FÄ for processing.
Article 8 of Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 sets a maximum period of three months from the date of receipt of the request for its processing.
All RFIs exchanged between the Czech Republic and Germany during the audited period have been examined by the NK.
Out of a total of 94 RFIs received from Germany, 70 cases (i.e. 74.5%) were dealt with within the three-month period; in a further 23 cases (i.e. 24.5%), this processing period was exceeded.
In the remaining one case, no reply had been sent to Germany pending examination by the NK. More detailed information on the deadlines within which requests made by Germany were answered by the Czech Republic can be found in Figure 2.
Out of the total number of 335 requests for information (RFI) sent to Germany from the Czech Republic, a reply was received in 136 cases (i.e. 40.6%) within the three-month period; a further 179 (i.e. 53.4%) were processed after the expiry of this period and, in 19 cases, no reply had been received from Germany (in the remaining one case, it was not possible to find out when the information was given).
More detailed information on the deadlines for responding to requests for information from the Czech Republic from Germany can be found in Figure 3.
