The chart above shows that the sales audited in connection with requests for information were mostly worth over €60,000.
The international exchange of information without prior request is either automatic, structured automatically or in the form of spontaneous information.
Financial officials from other Member States are often provided with information without prior request, which is important for setting the VAT liability.
In the Czech Republic, all information is collected from the CLO.
The exchange of information between the individual Member States takes place electronically.
"Automatic exchange" in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 means the systematic transmission of pre-determined information to other Member States at regular, pre-determined intervals without prior request.
"Structured automatic exchange" means the systematic transfer of previously determined information to another Member State, without its prior request, as soon as the information in question is available.
In the automatic exchange of information, the Czech Republic informs the other Member States about deliveries of new vehicles.
The financial officer receives this information from the pre-print notification of the delivery of a new vehicle in accordance with Section 19 of Law No. 235 / 2004, as well as from the copy of the invoice issued.
When processing this form, the financial officer inserts the required data into the relevant document template and forwards it directly to the responsible staff of the financial directorate, where this data is collected and sent to the CLO for further processing, after which these data will be transmitted to the other Member States within the specified period, namely within two months at the latest after the end of the quarter in which they were obtained.
The Czech Republic also provides information to other Member States on mail-order transactions that are tax-free in the country of origin, on intra-Community transactions that appear to be inadmissible and on potential "missing traders."
This information will be transmitted to the other Member States by means of an SCAC form in a spontaneous exchange of information.
Implementation of the international exchange of information in Germany
In Germany, the initiative for requests for information and spontaneous exchange of information comes from the local FA.
The FÄ will send the completed SCAC 2004 preprint directly to the German CLO via e-mail, which will forward the SCAC pre-prints to the foreign CLO.
The FÄ are instructed to write their requests for information or spontaneous information only in German, even the SCACpre-print used is unique.
Half of the German requests for information examined by the BRH were sent in order to ensure employment taxation in the other Member State, or to prove the tax exemption of intra-Community deliveries from Germany to the other Member State.
If the German CLO receives a request for information from another Member State, it will check whether the value of the deliveries mentioned in the request exceeds the minimum amount of €15,000.
If there is no reasonable justification for the request, the German CLO refuses to provide information on a turnover that is below the minimum amount limit.
In addition, the German CLO is concerned about the translation of the freely worded texts in the SCAC preprint [(B1-17) or (E)], if they are not written in German or English.
In response to the request for information, the CLO directs it to the relevant FA, referring to the three-month period.
No further deadlines have been set at the various levels of the German financial administration.
Although the German CLO has the technical means to monitor compliance with the deadline, it does not have the necessary staffing capacity to remind the FÄ to respond to the unfinished requests for information.
The FÄ will receive the information they need by writing to the tax authorities or carrying out an external audit.
The external auditors usually choose between two forms of audit: The VAT special audit, which covers all tax-sensitive transactions within a period of several months, or the so-called VAT review, which may only refer to a recent transaction.
In this short and concise form of examination, it is not necessary to make an announcement to the tax authorities, and it has proved its worth in the investigation of a single turnover.
In the case of the automatic exchange of information, Germany will provide the other Member State with the following information: - via UST-IdNr., which has been allocated to companies established in other EC Member States - on the refund of the input tax to traders established in other EC Member States.
In addition, Germany has agreed to provide the following information to the other EC Member States as part of the structured automatic exchange of information:
A. The delivery of new vehicles to entrepreneurs without UStIdNr., b. Distance sales (mail order) to other EC Member States, which are not subject to turnover tax in Germany, c. Significant deviations between the purchases reported by a tax authority and the MIAS data transmitted by other Member States, i.e. intra-Community deliveries of goods that have been improperly subject to taxation in Germany, have already been misused, or have been misappropriated by the Community.
Comparison and evaluation
The sending of requests for information or spontaneous information is carried out both in the Czech Republic and in Germany on the initiative of the local FÄ, who transmit the corresponding SCACpre-printed information to the CLO.
While the Czech CLO uses bilingual SCACpre-prints (Czech-English) and translates information provided into English or German, the German FÄ follow the instructions, requests for information or spontaneous information on a one-language preprint only in German.
The German CLO does not produce translations of German texts.
When examining requests for information between the Czech Republic and Germany in the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005, the NAC found that the Czech financial administration completed 74.5% of requests for information received within the three-month period, while the requests for information addressed to Germany were only completed in 40.6% of cases within that period.
Although the German CLO refers the FÄ to the three-month period, it does not monitor its compliance.
Due to the lack of memories, there is a high proportion of requests for information that have been answered for a limited period of time.
For this reason, the BRH has recommended to the German CLO a continuous process of remembrance.
The situation has now changed.
According to the information available to us, the German CLO is now reminding the tax authorities to respond to the outstanding requests for information.
Value-added tax risk management
Risk management in the Czech Republic
In the Czech Republic, several organisational units at different levels of financial management are involved in risk management in the area of turnover tax.
Within the Czech Ministry of Finance, the following organisational units are responsible for risk management and the fight against VAT fraud:
The Department for Methodology and Economic Management of Value Added Tax, or its risk management unit, is looking at identifying potential risk areas for tax revenue and evaluating trends in these risks in domestic and intra-Community trade.
At the national level, this body coordinates the criteria for "the credibility of VAT returns" and uses the MIAS data to detect potential tax evasion within the framework of intra-Community deliveries and acquisitions.
Based on data on the trade balance of the Czech Republic, it evaluates high-risk goods, prepares the risk management in the area of turnover tax conceptually and cooperates in this area with the relevant EC institutions and the other Member States.
The department for international mutual assistance in the area of value added tax provides, among other things, for the exchange of information, contributes to the creation and implementation of a relevant information database, evaluates the data available in the MIAS system in other Member States, carries out public relations work and is responsible for other forms of intergovernmental mutual assistance within the meaning of Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003.
