The Tax Audit and Investigation Methodology Department conducts, among other things, risk analyses within the framework of the methodological management of tax audits, sets out priorities for the work planning of the financial directorates with regard to the selection of cases to be examined, compiles risk analyses to combat tax evasion and, in this context, collects information from the financial administration and other sources, and makes proposals for measures to combat tax evasion.
Tax investigators are in charge of the financial directorates. Their tasks include the search for tax evaders and industries that are at risk in terms of the frequency of tax evasion (e.g. internet transactions, gold, pharmaceutical industry), the search for unregistered tax evaders (e.g. in the sectors of internet services, employment services, electronic and print media, etc.), the investigation of misappropriation in the case of chain fraud.
Special examination units have been set up in 12 selected FÄ.
They have a regional competence and, on the basis of appropriate authorisation, carry out tax audits outside the local jurisdiction of the FÄ.
The need to set up the special audit units arose from the increase in the number of new and "improved" forms of tax evasion, particularly in the context of chain transactions.
These special units check according to the needs of tax investigators, or focus on tax professionals with specific activities, multinational companies, and tax professionals with particularly high turnover.
The following mechanisms for reducing the risks in the area of value added tax have been integrated into the Atis system: - the task of "credibility of VAT returns" to assess the risk of tax returns, - the task of "selecting the tax authorities to be audited," selecting the tax authorities to be audited on the basis of certain criteria - the task of "MIAS," which provides financial officials with access to the data provided by the other EC Member States.
The "MIAS" task allows, among other things, the following: - verification of the validity of the UST ID number of tax payers from other Member States, - confirmation of the value of the goods delivered to a Czech tax authority, as stated in the zm of all suppliers of the tax revenue from other Member States, tax returns from other Member States, tax returns from other Member States, and tax returns from those Member States, which have not been submitted to them, - formal control of the information in the tax information in the Czech Republic.
As part of their mission to fight tax evasion, financial officials have access to data from state authorities such as commercial registers, land registry offices, motor vehicle registrars, business registers, etc.
More detailed information on this can be found in section 4.4.1 of the submission and processing of the summary reports in the Czech Republic.
Risk management in Germany
In the Federal Republic of Germany, due to their federal structure, both the federal financial authorities (in particular the CLO) and the financial authorities of the 16 federal states are involved in the development and introduction of an RMS.
Although there are joint working groups for development, neither the CLO nor the financial authorities of the federal states have a fully unified set of data.
At the level of the CLO, the ST I 2 unit (hereinafter referred to as the "Kuss" - Coordinating Centre for Sales Tax Examining and Tax Investigation Measures) collects the audit findings on cases of fraud in the Opus database.
In cooperation with the countries, another database called Zauber was set up at the kiss, where the tax offices can enter and query the names of discovered missing traders or sales tax fraudsters.
The Kuss coordinates both related cases of VAT fraud at the national level and cases of cross-border VAT fraud.
The experience of the kiss will be incorporated into the development of the RMS through their participation in the working groups.
In addition, experts from several other organizational units of the CLO and the BMF are also involved.
The formal review of the composition of UStIdNr. of other Member States, which appear in the German tax authorities, will be carried out by the CLO.
This formal review takes place before the ZM is sent to other Member States in order to improve the reliability of the MIAS data and, therefore, its usefulness (see 4.4.2).
The validation of the validity in the so-called UST ID number is carried out on the basis of the O _ MCTL identifiers provided by the other Member States (for the procedure for correcting invalid UST ID, see also 4.4.2).
In addition, the CLO's RMS is based on MIAS data provided by other Member States and generates various types of communications to detect suspected missing traders. As evidence, certain features are used, which usually occur in carousel transactions.
The FÄ of the federal states are instructed to process these communications and have to forward the results of their investigations to the CLO in certain cases.
The BRH audit has confirmed that all available features need to be included in order to be sufficiently likely to suggest a case of tax fraud (rather than focusing mainly on a company's turnover).
Accordingly, the BRH has advised the BMF to work with combinations of different clues in the preparation of the messages.
The risk management system should also take into account other points of reference, such as the payment behaviour of the tax payer, the industry or the company's shareholding.
A second level of risk management exists with the financial authorities of the federal states and focuses on the processing of the VAT advance declarations and the annual declarations.
For example, the system compiles a list of those who have indicated intra-Community deliveries in their VAT advance notification or annual declaration.
This list will be sent to the CLO to monitor the full delivery of the ZM.
Furthermore, in this type of risk management, the purchases indicated by the tax collector in his annual tax return are compared with the data in the MIAS.
The financial authorities of the federal states avoid comparing the quarterly data, as these would result in too many inconsistencies due to factors other than tax evasion or tax fraud; for example:
- Supplier and acquirer are based on different dates for the execution of intra-Community turnover;
- Different accounting and tax declaration of Skonti and discounts.
In addition to comparing the information from the VAT returns with the MIAS data, many federal states have certain risk management mechanisms, which are based on information in the VAT returns and certain other indications (e.g. company wording, age of the owners / shareholders, number of employees and method of payment of the tax authorities).
Bavaria has introduced a rules-based risk management system that allows a team of tax fraud specialists (hereinafter referred to as "risk managers") to program their own rules in such a way that suspected tax fraudsters are singled out.
This system is used in the processing of the VAT advance reports by the FÄ.
As a result, the competent FA receives the advice of the RMS before the turnover tax is set.
As this system is not capable of learning, risk managers will have to adjust the rules according to the feedback from the FÄ.
Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania has developed an adaptive neuronal network based on the data of detected cases.
Based on this data, the RMS is able to learn the characteristics of tax evasion.
The system compiles a monthly list of tax cases where there is evidence of tax evasion.
On the basis of this list, the competent FÄ will decide on the audit of the tax authorities in question.
After the audit, the tax examiners will have to report their results so that the RMS can learn from the results of the tests it has proposed.
In North Rhine-Westphalia, an adaptive neural network is used in combination with a rules-based fuzzy system.
Based on a lot of data from processed sales tax returns and some other clues, this neuro-fuzzy system (also known as the datamining system) calculates how likely it is that a tax collector is involved in tax fraud.
It then compiles a monthly list of suspected tax fraudsters.
On the basis of this list, the FÄ select the tax authorities concerned for examination and report the audit results to the data centre in question.
The introduction of these three RMS is under way in the federal states.
Since each of these three risk management systems is based on a different approach, the combination of all three anti-fraud systems appears to be effective.
Whether the hoped-for effects will materialise in actual use remains to be seen.
Comparison and evaluation
Although it is not possible in the present report to deal with the specific criteria of the RMS in the Czech Republic and Germany, the NAC and the BRH have found that each Member State has developed its own RMS.
As well as the different approaches in the three German states mentioned above, the RMS of each European state has its particular strengths and weaknesses.
At the moment, there is an exchange of experience between the financial authorities of the European Member States on new trends and new models of cross-border VAT fraud.
VAT fraud - in particular carousel fraud - has proved to be not a national problem, but a European one.
The people involved in fraud coordinate their actions not only in one but in several Member States.
A Member State cannot develop an effective RMS on its own.
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in every EU Member State. If this is not the case, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS for their crimes.
The tax losses caused by Europe-wide VAT fraud do not necessarily affect the Member State in which the initiator is based.
Any other Member State involved in the fraud may be affected.
That is why there should be a European exchange of experience on the RMS.
Selected results from the audit of individual sales In the context of the parallel tests, the NK and the BRH examined the quality and usability of information on selected deliveries and / or
Which were the subject of the international exchange of information between the financial authorities of the Czech Republic and Germany.
In addition, the two courts jointly examined the handling of several deliveries, which were in doubt about their execution, or which the tax authorities of both states explained differently in their tax returns, or at least in different ways.
At the request of the BRH, the NK investigated a total of eight business transactions between eight Czech and eight German tax authorities.
In addition, in 43 cases, on the basis of BRH communications, the NK examined the values of intra-Community transactions with Germany, which Czech tax authorities had stated in their tax returns and zm.
At the request of the NK, the BRH reviewed a total of 23 deliveries between 23 German and 21 Czech tax evaders.
The relevant information was exchanged exclusively on the basis of Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003 on CLO.
The examination of the selected cases showed, among other things, that the different registration procedures in the EC Member States lead to the problems mentioned in Chapter 4.1:
1.
According to MIAS data, in the third quarter of 2004, a Czech tax collector purchased goods worth €60,500 from a German tax collector.
When the Czech tax authorities declared an acquisition of only €29,869, the Czech financial administration sent a request for information to Germany in order to verify the value of the goods delivered.
In response to the Czech request for information, the German side stated that the German tax authority in question had delivered goods worth €27,381 to its Czech business partner in the second quarter of 2004, €31,997 in the third quarter and €10,276 in the fourth quarter.
Furthermore, it emerged from the reply that the UST ID number of the German tax authority was only valid from 28 September 2004. However, the German CLO had accepted a further request from the German tax authority and had brought forward the validity of the UST ID number retroactively to 1 May 2004.
The German tax watchdog corrected the zm.
On the basis of this information, it was a (intra-Community) purchase of goods by the Czech tax authorities.
In a request to the competent tax office in the Czech Republic, the NK found that, in 2004, the Czech tax authority had issued supplementary VAT returns for the individual (lower-year) tax periods in which it declared a higher value of purchases from other Member States, while at the same time seeking the deduction of pre-tax from purchases from other Member States.
On the basis of these additional VAT declarations, the responsible person in charge of the Czech tax office could not clearly determine whether the value of the deliveries of the above-mentioned German supplier was also included in the declared acquisitions.
In response to a request for information from the NK, the BRH found that the German supplier had been registered in September 2003 as subject to VAT.
At the time of registration, however, he had not applied for the allocation of a UST-IdNr., but only a tax number, which ultimately applies to Germany.
Although it is generally not possible in Germany to retroactively assign a UST ID number to a tax payer, in 2006 the responsible person in charge of the German financial administration did so retroactively as of 1 May 2004.
The German CLO grants a UST ID number retroactively if the deut entrepreneur has not caused the delayed allocation; for example, if the CLO caused the delay following a request from the tax collector to grant a UST ID number.
In this case, the CLO grants the UST ID number retroactively, because the entrepreneur does not require a valid UST ID number for an intra-Community delivery according to Section 6 of the USTG.
Conversely, a German acquirer does not need the (valid) UST ID number of its supplier to explain the intra-community acquisition.
Because of these procedural differences between the Member States, the German CLO issued the UST ID number retroactively in this particular case.
