As part of the international exchange of information, the German finance official reviewed the purchase of goods in the first quarter of 2005 by a Czech tax collector of €22,686 from a German tax collector.
In a request to the local competent tax official in the Czech Republic, the NK found that the Czech financial officer had checked with the Czech tax officer during an external audit whether the intra-municipal delivery had actually taken place and whether the Czech tax officer had booked and paid the invoice for the delivery of the goods.
The Czech tax collector did not explain the intra-communal acquisition in his VAT return, because the German supplier did not specify his VAT ID number in the invoice, but only his tax number for transactions within Germany.
According to the MIAS data, the German tax collector will not be registered for the turnover tax in connection with intra-Community sales until 21 April 2005, i.e. after delivery to the Czech tax authorities.
The Czech finance official also requested that the German tax administration send a copy of the registration certificate of the German tax collector, so that he could initiate an appropriate tax procedure if necessary.
The Czech FA considered this business to be the purchase of goods from a non-business (private) person in Germany and therefore did not impose any sales tax on the purchase of the goods from Germany.
The BRH found that, under German law, a tax collector who supplies goods to other Member States does not have to have a VAT ID number for intra-Community deliveries in order to be able to claim the VAT exemption for such a shipment.
The supplier must only have the purchaser's UStId number in the other Member State and must be able to prove that the goods in question have been transported to the other Member State.
In this case, the turnover under German tax law is a (tax-exempt) intra-Community supply, which should be subject to employment tax in the Czech Republic.
In any case, it is important that the Czech financial officer took note of this business incident, because the delivery of a machine of this value was not part of the core business of the German supplier.
