With the German reply to this request, three invoices were sent, which showed a total value of the delivered goods of €31,999, i.e. an amount corresponding to the difference between the purchase declared by the Czech tax authorities and the MIAS data.
In a request to the local Czech financial officer, the NAC stated that after receiving the reply from Germany, he had contacted the accountant of the Czech tax authority and remained with her in such a way that, after checking the invoices, she wanted to talk with the company owner about issuing a supplementary VAT return for the third quarter of 2004.
So far, no additional VAT return has been issued.
The Czech financial official told the NK that he would proceed in such a way that the deadlines for a retroactive VAT setting for the tax period in question would be respected.
17.
In the fourth quarter of 2004, the German tax authorities delivered goods worth €11,600 to the German tax authorities.
In the context of the intergovernmental exchange of information, the German financial official asked for an examination of whether the aforementioned Czech tax authorities actually existed, as the alleged capital owner of the German tax authorities had set up a number of bogus funds in Germany.
In the course of the FA's review of the transaction, the Czech tax authorities confirmed the purchase of the goods.
According to the Czech tax authorities, however, the goods were not shipped from Germany to the Czech Republic, but were sold on in Germany in 2005.
The Czech tax expert presented evidence of the sale in January 2005.
The Czech tax collector was not registered in Germany as subject to VAT and had not taxed the sale of the goods in question either in the Czech Republic or in Germany.
All of these facts pointed to tax evasion within Germany, and the Czech finance official provided this information in his response to the request for information to the German financial administration.
In a request to the local Czech financial officer, the NK found that the Czech tax collector had filed a supplementary tax return for the fourth quarter of 2004 on the basis of a tax audit, in which, among other things, he declared the value of the goods he had purchased from a German tax collector and, at the same time, asserted the right of deduction for the purchase from other Member States.
In his Czech sales tax return, he did not register any sales tax on the sale of goods in Germany.
On the basis of a supplementary VAT return, which had been issued after the external audit, the Czech financial officer fixed the VAT liability unchanged.
According to Czech law, in this case, there was no purchase of goods from other Member States, as the goods were not shipped or transported from another Member State to the Czech Republic.
As a result, the Czech financial officer drew the wrong conclusion during the external audit.
The BRH found that immediately after receiving the reply to the request for information, which showed that the goods had not left Germany, the German financial official corrected the tax return of the German tax collector and demanded the payment of VAT worth €1,600.
In addition, the relevant FA sent a control notice to the FA responsible for the actual recipient of the goods, in order to ensure that the resale of these goods is properly taxed.
In the following cases, contractors declared intra-community deliveries that may not have been carried out:
18.
The Czech finance official received a request for information from the German tax administration on whether the Czech tax collector had purchased a car worth €47,400 from the German tax authority in February 2005.
The request for information was accompanied as an attachment by an imprint of the VAT registration certificate of the Czech tax authorities.
A photocopy of the passport was attached to the person who was supposed to have carried the vehicle.
In the course of his investigation, the Czech financial officer found that the passport had been stolen, that the person named in it had not imported a vehicle into the Czech Republic and stated that he had no contact with a German tax collector.
The VAT registration certificate, the imprint of which had been sent by the German side, had not been issued by the Czech financial administration.
With this information, the Czech financial officer responded to the request for information and, at the same time, stated that he could not confirm the purchase of the car.
In a request to the local Czech financial officer, the NK stated that the Czech tax collector does not have his seat at the address indicated in the Commercial Register and that the managing director of the company is not available.
Following a tax complaint procedure for the tax period of February 2005, the Czech financial officer set the tax liability of the Czech tax collector at zero.
As part of a further investigation, the Czech finance official found that the vehicle in question had been sold to another Czech person who had purchased it on the basis of an internet advertisement.
The BRH found that the local German financial official had rejected the German tax authority's claim to exempt this delivery from VAT on the basis of the Czech response to the request for information.
19. In the course of an external audit, a German FA was unable to clarify a difference of €3,000 between the value of the goods purchased in the VAT return and the reported values from other Member States.
A Czech tax collector should have delivered goods worth €89,424 to a German tax collector in the fourth quarter of 2004 and in the first quarter of 2005.
Since the acquisition declared by the German tax authorities was not in line with the MIAS data, the German financial officer asked for verification of the deliveries and their payment as part of the intergovernmental exchange of information.
In his response to the request for information, the Czech finance official said that the only managing director of the Czech company had been deleted from the commercial register on 8 July 2005 and that a new managing director had not yet been registered.
The German recipient of the goods was presumed to be a relative of the shareholder of the Czech company.
The Czech tax collector issued a VAT return and a ZM, which had been signed by a person not authorised to do so, namely the company's shareholder, following the deletion of the managing director in the Commercial Register.
The accountant of the Czech tax office informed the financial officer that the owner of the capital had deposited the payment received for the invoiced goods in euros into the company's account.
Cash receipts have not been issued.
In a request to the local Czech FA, the NK found that the financial officer had accepted the Czech tax authority's claim for VAT exemption for goods delivered to other Member States, worth CZK 1,326,307 in the first quarter of 2004 and CZK 1,416,180 in the first quarter of 2005.
The BRH found that the German financial officer did not correct the German buyer's VAT return, as in the meantime a German court had confirmed the insolvency of the German tax collector.
Since the previous external audit showed no evidence of tax fraud, there is no prospect of actually being able to collect a fixed VAT liability.
20. According to the MIAS data, a German tax collector purchased goods from the Czech Republic worth €4,251,196 in 2005, according to which he had purchased goods worth €43,274 in the previous year.
The German tax expert did not explain the intra-Community acquisitions either in his 2004 tax return or in the 2005 tax return.
In addition, he did not declare any corresponding initial sales in terms of value.
Due to these inconsistencies, the German FA submitted a request for information regarding the fourth quarter of 2005 and the first quarter of 2006.
In the ZM for these two quarters, a Czech supplier reported intra-community deliveries of goods totaling CZK 167,246,083.
On 6 September 2006, the request for information was received, in which the German side requested to check whether the delivery reported by the Czech tax authorities had actually taken place.
In response to this request for information, the Czech Finance Administration stated that the German request could not be complied with because the Czech company did not have a managing director (or other legal representative).
It can be seen from the documents provided to the NK by the competent financial officer that, together with the managing director of the Czech tax authority, a protocol was drawn up on 30 March 2006 on the commencement of the VAT audit for the fourth quarter of 2004 and the period from January to December 2005.
At the same time, the tax payer was asked by the financial officer to submit all accounting and tax documents for this period, but failed to do so.
According to the Commercial Register, the term of office of the sole managing director expired on 16 May 2005 without the appointment of a new managing director.
The Czech tax collector has not issued any tax returns since April 2006.
As part of the parallel investigation, the NK, in collaboration with the BRH, investigated several cases of intra-Community deliveries between the Czech Republic and Germany, which were not the subject of a prior exchange of information between the two countries.
The two audit bodies exchanged information on the cases examined through the CLO of both countries.
21. A Czech company (UCR), which is not based in Germany, informed the relevant FA (Chemnitz-Süd) that it wanted to do tax-sensitive business in Germany.
On the basis of this information, the company was registered as of June 2005, but did not receive a German UST-IdNr.
The (UCR) accepted an order from a Danish company (UDK) for the production of wind turbines and their delivery to Austria on behalf of, at the risk and for the account of the Danish customer.
Due to insufficient own production capacity, the Danish company passed on part of the contract to a German tax authority (Ude), which is based in Germany.
The following illustration depicts the contractual relations and the transport route of the wind turbines:
According to German law, the place of performance of these transactions must be determined as described below:
- The Danish company (UDK) sent the wind turbines on its behalf, at its risk and for its own account to be installed in Austria.
Due to the installation, its delivery will take place in Austria, i.e. the delivery of the wind turbines will be controllable in Austria.
- Because the forwarder was commissioned by the Danish company (UDK) and the latter had the transport carried out in his own name, at his own risk and for his own account, the place of delivery of the German sub-contractor (Ude) is where the transport started, i.e. in Germany.
Although the wind turbines were delivered to another EC Member State (AU) and the recipient is registered as subject to tax in an EC Member State (CR), no tax exemption could be claimed for the delivery of the German sub-contractor (Ude), as the EC Member State for which the delivery was intended is different from the seat state of the Czech company 19.
Accordingly, the delivery is properly taxed in Germany, and the Czech company (UCR) claimed the deduction in its VAT returns.
The location of the delivery of the Czech company (UCR) also depends on the place where the transport started.
However, some of the wind turbines were transported from the Czech Republic and others from Germany.
- The delivery of wind turbines manufactured in the Czech Republic took place in the Czech Republic.
- The delivery of the remaining wind turbines, which were manufactured in Germany, took place in Germany.
Accordingly, the Czech company (UCR) delivered both intra-Community deliveries from the Czech Republic to Austria as well as intra-Community deliveries from Germany to Austria.
The BRH found that the Czech company (UCR) did not declare in its German tax returns or in its domestic deliveries to the German CLO.
As a result, the Czech company may have treated all its intra-Community deliveries uniformly as intra-Community deliveries from the Czech Republic.
The NAC found that (UCR) did not report intra-Community deliveries to Austria, but intra-Community deliveries to Denmark.
In order to ensure the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions in Austria, it would be necessary to cooperate with at least four financial administrations (the Austrian, Czech, Danish and German), although in this case there are no signs of tax fraud or tax evasion.
In addition, the NAC and the BRH examined case designs in order to show the size of the differences caused by the different legislation in 2004 between the information in the VAT returns and the MIAS data.
The cases examined also show that it will take some time for the tax authorities and the FÄ to apply the new legislation:
22. In its zm for the second, third and fourth quarters of 2004, a Czech tax collector reported deliveries of goods totaling CZK 792,977,452 to a German tax collector.
During the same period, another Czech tax collector reported a total value of CZK 18,157,265 in his intra-Community deliveries to another German tax collector.
From the information provided by the BRH to the NK, it emerged that in both cases it was a matter of electricity supplies.
Both Czech tax authorities took into account the above-mentioned deliveries in accordance with Czech Law No 235 / 2004, which was in force in 2004.
In a further examination of these transactions, an audit group of the NK found that in 2004 there were different legal regulations governing the supply or acquisition of electrical energy between the Czech Republic and Germany.
Whereas in the Czech Republic the tax authorities declared the deliveries of electrical energy to be intra-Community deliveries in accordance with the provisions of Law No. 235 / 2004 in force in 2004, according to the German legislation in force in 2004 it was not an intra-Community purchase of goods, but taxable and tax-sensitive sales in Germany.
The differences in the legal provisions were eliminated in the Czech Republic by the adoption of Law No 635 / 2004, which amended some tax provisions with effect from 1 January 2005.
23. In the examination of intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions in cooperation with the BRH, it was further established that a Czech tax collector, in his ZM for the first and fourth quarter of 2005, made intra-Community deliveries to a German tax collector with a total value of CZK 240,411,163, and another Czech tax controller, in his ZM for the same period, declared intra-Community deliveries to another German tax collector at C3.76.
Information sent from the BRH to the NK showed that in both cases it was a matter of supplies of electrical energy.
In accordance with the wording of Law No 235 / 2004, which will apply from 1 January 2005, the place of performance for the supply of electrical energy is the place where the purchaser has his legal seat, place of business or place of business for which the delivery takes place.
For this reason, the Czech tax authorities should not have indicated the electricity deliveries in their zm for 2005.
The fact that both controllers treated the supply of electrical energy in their zm as intra-Community deliveries led to a pay difference of CZK 503,881,939 in MIAS.
Conclusion
Through the cooperation, the goals of the BRH and the NK have been achieved.
Both auditors gained in-depth knowledge of the systems of VAT management in the Czech Republic and Germany.
The cooperation revealed differences in the two systems and in the legal regulations that govern the VAT administration.
During the parallel examinations, interesting cases of intra-community deliveries or acquisitions were revealed.
For some of them, it is worth further observation.
On the basis of the audit results, both audit bodies drew up recommendations on the management of turnover tax.
The follow-up of these recommendations in the form of a review should be part of the follow-up.
The new experience and knowledge gained through the collaboration between the two audit bodies is the basis for the successful conduct of future audits in the area of VAT administration.
